<div id="review_32848670" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/32848670" />
    <a title="Sara" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/1166296-sara"><img alt="Sara" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1619372372p2/1166296.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/32848670?book_show_action=true">Sep 14, 2008</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Sara" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Sara" href="/user/show/1166296-sara">Sara</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>


          <div><span class="uitext greyText">Recommends it for: </span>
           <span class="uitext reviewText">everyone, especially parents and teachers</span></div>

        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer32848670" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer14930050123258426255">An excellent book! I am at a loss as to how to review this book... I think the key is that it brings understanding to childhood- an understanding, or perhaps a new perspective, more valuable and important than words can do justice. <br/><br/>My impression is that Montessori&apos;s approach is in the first place scientific, and that from it springs great love. A treat for me was the religious, Catholic insights that sprinkle the pages.<br/><br/>I don&apos;t remember what struck me most when I first read much of this book in J</span>
  <span id="freeText14930050123258426255" style="display:none">An excellent book! I am at a loss as to how to review this book... I think the key is that it brings understanding to childhood- an understanding, or perhaps a new perspective, more valuable and important than words can do justice. <br /><br />My impression is that Montessori's approach is in the first place scientific, and that from it springs great love. A treat for me was the religious, Catholic insights that sprinkle the pages.<br /><br />I don't remember what struck me most when I first read much of this book in June, but this time around there is no question, two things in particular: when Montessori relates an incident where the teacher of her first classroom tried punishment (time out) with no success but was met with apathy. Just the reminder I needed (need) at the time: children aren't motivated by punishment and reward. What a comfort for me, for lack of a better word, that Montessori once encountered difficulty in this area as well. Her response? "Eventually we gave up either punishing or rewarding the children." (My understanding: the key being the environment leading to the creation of inner/self-discipline).<br /><br />My other favorite part is the story she relates of teaching the children how to blow one's nose. She expected laughter as she demonstrated but was surprised that the children erupted in applause! And upon leaving was met with a chorus of "thank you for the lesson!" She tells us the reason why, which she said other observations also confirmed: children were always being scolded for having running noses, suffering the indignity of being sent off to school with handkerchiefs blatantly pinned to their clothing, etc., all of which caused them great humiliation. But blowing the nose is difficult for children and no one had ever thought or bothered to show/teach them how to do it!! Here was a liberation, a granting of a sense of dignity. All of this shows the mistakes we, as adults, all too often make: we don't regard the child with dignity and respect, we underestimate them and their sense of "personhood," and we fail to see things through their perspective.<br /><br /><br />Here are some of my favorite quotes from The Secret of Childhood:<br /><br />"If [a child] is to develop his personality, it is necessary that the adult should hold himself in check and follow the lead given by the child. And he should regard it as a privilege that he is able to understand and follow him."<br /><br />"Christ appears to men also under the guise of a child."<br /><br />"after a child is given an object [in the classroom] to use, he not only continues to work with it, but his efforts leave him mentally stronger and healthier than before. It took time to persuade me that this was not an illusion... How often it happened that I reproved the teacher when she told me what the children were doing! 'Don't come to tell me such fantasies...' she, without being offended, would tearfully reply: 'You are right. When I see such things I think that it must be the angels who are inspiring these children.'"<br /><br />"[The teacher] told me: 'They do so exactly what I tell them that I am beginning to feel responsible for every word I say.'"<br /><br />"To those who do not understand its true nature, original sin may seem unjust an unreasonable since it involves the condemnation of all of Adam's descendants. And yet we see under our very eyes innocent children condemned to carry within themselves the fatal consequences of centuries of error with respect to their natural development."<br /><br />"Like other living creatures [man] should give up his own way of acting [in favor of the child] and make a holocaust of himself so that life may be carried forward towards eternity." </span>
  <a data-text-id="14930050123258426255" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


