<div id="review_1730437815" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1730437815" />
    <a title="Talia" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/3037210-talia"><img alt="Talia" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1265862083p2/3037210.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1730437815?book_show_action=true">Aug 16, 2016</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Talia" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Talia" href="/user/show/3037210-talia">Talia</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1730437815" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer2498261606039175624">I loved reading this primary text from Maria Montessori herself -- so good to hear what she was really thinking. This book is better than &apos;The Absorbent Mind.&apos; Reading MM&apos;s own words helps me to understand (and take with a grain of salt) some of the interpretations of her observations and instructions as manifest in Montessori groups on Facebook / other communities. For example, the thing about not (over) praising children seems to be really hyped up in certain conversations about Montessori met</span>
  <span id="freeText2498261606039175624" style="display:none">I loved reading this primary text from Maria Montessori herself -- so good to hear what she was really thinking. This book is better than 'The Absorbent Mind.' Reading MM's own words helps me to understand (and take with a grain of salt) some of the interpretations of her observations and instructions as manifest in Montessori groups on Facebook / other communities. For example, the thing about not (over) praising children seems to be really hyped up in certain conversations about Montessori method, but MM just found that when children do work that they find truly satisfying, they don't NEED or SEEK OUT praise. When provided with the proper materials to work with, they can self-correct their own errors and take their own joy in what they are doing. In fact, much of what MM says is that we need to get out of our children's way -- they already have it in them to do so much, but their efforts at person-building are often thwarted by the most important people in their lives: their parents especially, and also educators and caretakers. The book includes many poignant statements about the incredible responsibility and opportunity that parents have to help their children make their own way in the world. A few of the many, many things I highlighted:<br /><br />"We must wake up to the great reality that children have a psychic life whose delicate manifestations escape notice and whose pattern of activity can be unconsciously disrupted by adults." <br /><br />"A child must start from nothing and make his way into the company of adults. In comparison with the child an adult is great and powerful like a god, and it is from him that the child must obtain the necessities of life. The adult is the child's creator, ruler, guardian, and benefactor. Never is anyone so utterly dependent upon another as a child is upon an adult."<br /><br />From a chapter on The Intelligence of Love: "What an adult tells a child remains engraved on his mind as if it had been cut in marble...Since children are so eager to learn and so burning with love, an adult should carefully weigh all of the words he speaks before them." <br /><br />Also: "A child's tantrums and rebellions are nothing more than aspects of a vital conflict between his creative impulses and his love for an adult who fails to understand his needs."<br /><br /> "A child gains experience through exercise and movement. He coordinates his own movements and records the emotions he experiences in coming into contact with the external world. These help to mold his intelligence...By means of his constant efforts, experiences, sorrows, and conquests of difficult trials and struggles, a child slowly perfects his activities. An adult can assist in shaping the environment, but it is the child who perfects his own being."</span>
  <a data-text-id="2498261606039175624" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


