<div id="review_1239141427" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1239141427" />
    <a title="Sarah" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/732395-sarah"><img alt="Sarah" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1199248326p2/732395.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1239141427?book_show_action=true">Mar 28, 2015</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Sarah" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Sarah" href="/user/show/732395-sarah">Sarah</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/732395-sarah?shelf=parenting">parenting</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1239141427" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer16471650088894634970">I&apos;ve been interested in Montessori style education since having my son, and we have implemented some Montessori ideas in his room and with his toys/learning materials (a floor bed in his room, toys and books within reach, simple stacking and sorting toys...along with the inevitable V Tech talking things) This is her first book I believe, and details out how she got started working in schools with children. I find many of her ideas about childhood and children ring very true, and I definitely bel</span>
  <span id="freeText16471650088894634970" style="display:none">I've been interested in Montessori style education since having my son, and we have implemented some Montessori ideas in his room and with his toys/learning materials (a floor bed in his room, toys and books within reach, simple stacking and sorting toys...along with the inevitable V Tech talking things) This is her first book I believe, and details out how she got started working in schools with children. I find many of her ideas about childhood and children ring very true, and I definitely believe that children benefit from a good, intellectually stimulating environment, and from parents doing less rather than more many times. Some of her ideas were a bit odd to me, such as the idea that children really have no need to play, but rather want to work. I can definitely see that my son loves working at a skill, but it is very playlike as well. I think they notion of "play/work" for kids maybe has evolved in our heads, partly due to Montessori herself? I certainly see that he loves repeating motions and tasks over and over til he gets good at them. I try to allow him ample time to do these things and try not to interrupt if he is hard at work with something like fitting a cup into another cup. But I also see that he is playful in his interactions with the world. He loves playing dolls for instance, and pretending to have them walk and play with toys themselves. In any case, I'm not really hung up over it. I do think that her description of her children at the schools as perfectly behaved and quiet is odd, and not what I expect my son to be like as a preschooler. Of course, those kids at her school were given plenty of freedom to wiggle, get up, move around as they needed, they had freedom to go outside if they wanted too. Our schools need more of that!!</span>
  <a data-text-id="16471650088894634970" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


