    <div class="elementListBrownSeparator"></div>



  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1075587956" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1075587956" />
    <a title="Bernardo Villela" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/3470596-bernardo-villela"><img alt="Bernardo Villela" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1442969075p2/3470596.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1075587956?book_show_action=true">Oct 08, 2014</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Bernardo Villela" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Bernardo Villela" href="/user/show/3470596-bernardo-villela">Bernardo Villela</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1075587956" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer8240310455887573697">Having attended a Montessori school from K-4 it was illuminating to read this account from the literal mother of the method. What was most impressive is how much of the educational philosophy is imbued in the experience of being in that educational environment and verbalized in this writing. Furthermore, as a new parent, it has a multi-faceted approach to discussing child development, psychology, and sociological conditions that affect growth, and also serve as reminders and insights to ones own</span>
  <span id="freeText8240310455887573697" style="display:none">Having attended a Montessori school from K-4 it was illuminating to read this account from the literal mother of the method. What was most impressive is how much of the educational philosophy is imbued in the experience of being in that educational environment and verbalized in this writing. Furthermore, as a new parent, it has a multi-faceted approach to discussing child development, psychology, and sociological conditions that affect growth, and also serve as reminders and insights to ones own childhood. As well as a brief, fleeting glimpse in the mind of a child. <br /><br />Much of the closing chapters iterates in an adult voice what I felt growing up, and still hold on to about the role and general disregard for youth in society that must continue to be corrected. <br /><br />It's not strictly about parenting, as only the very last chapter is directly aimed at parents; however, it is full of information on children, parenthood, education, nature, science, and more; and I'm glad to consider it the first book on parenting I read.</span>
  <a data-text-id="8240310455887573697" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


